SIMPLE: subserviency
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Subserviency
<hw>Sub*serv"i*en*cy</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being
subservient; instrumental fitness or use; hence, willingness to serve
another's purposes; in a derogatory sense, servility.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The body wherein appears much fitness, use, and
<qex>subserviency</qex> to infinite functions.</q>
<rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a regular subordination and <qex>subserviency</qex> among
all the parts to beneficial ends.</q> <rj><qau>Cheyne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Subservient</ent>⟦br⟧
